'''Nakawada Rock-Cut Tomb Cluster''' (中和田横穴墓群) is a {{ill|rock-cut tomb cluster|ja|横穴墓群|1=Cave tomb|lt=Cave tombs|12=draft}} located in Nakawada, {{ill|Tama City|ja|多摩市|12=draft}}, Tokyo, Japan. It is the largest cluster of its kind in the Tama region.

== Overview ==
The cluster is distributed along the south-facing slopes of the Nakawada area.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Tokyo Metropolitan Regional Education Support Division Management Section|url=https://tokyo-iseki.metro.tokyo.lg.jp/|title=Tokyo Archaeological Site map Internet Service|work=Tokyo Metropolitan Board of Education|accessdate=2024-04-24}}</ref> 

In 1976, an excavation of 14 tombs was conducted. These 14 tombs are grouped into two clusters and further divided into five groups. The floor plans of the burial chambers exhibit an evolutionary transition from single rectangular chambers to bilobed chambers and back to single rectangular chambers. These tombs are believed to have been constructed between the 7th and 8th centuries.

